ol.li:
A matrix is self-adjoint if
 \inprod{\uvec{u}}{A \uvec{v}} = \inprod{A \uvec{u}}{\uvec{v}} 
always, so that \adjoint{A} = A.

paragraphs.p:
Where necessary, in this discovery guide we will write
\amp {\inprod{\blank}{\blank}}_{\R} \text{,} \amp \amp {\inprod{\blank}{\blank}}_{\C}
to distinguish between the real and complex dot products, respectively.

introduction.p:
The Hermitian matrix
 H = \left[\begin{array}{rcc} 0 \amp \ci \amp 0 \\ -\ci \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right] 
has eigenvalues \lambda = \pm 1 with

	E_{-1}(H) \amp = \Span \left\{
		\left[\begin{array}{r} -\ci \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]
	\right\} \text{,}
	\amp
	E_1(H) \amp = \Span \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\} \text{.}

The complex matrix
 A = \left[\begin{array}{rrc} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ -2 \ci \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp 2 \ci \amp 1 \end{array}\right] 
has eigenvalues \lambda = \pm 1 with

	E_{-1}(A) \amp = \Span \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ \ci \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\} \text{,}
	\amp
	E_1(A) \amp = \Span \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\} \text{.}
